INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '908ccac7-f1e9-4008-9f36-55c9558d91e2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Node.js Concurrency — The Event Loop, Worker Threads, and Why async/await Isn't Parallelism$escape$,
  $escape$Node.js runs on a single-threaded event loop powered by libuv. async/await doesn't create threads — it yields control back to the event loop while waiting on I/O, letting other callbacks run. CPU-bound work still blocks the loop entirely.

For true parallelism, Node.js offers `worker_threads` (since v12). Each worker gets its own V8 isolate and event loop. You communicate via `MessageChannel` or `SharedArrayBuffer` — there's no shared memory by default, making data races unlikely.

Compare this to Go's goroutines (M:N green threads scheduled by the runtime) or Java's virtual threads (Project Loom). Node.js has no equivalent lightweight thread primitive — `worker_threads` are OS threads under the hood, making them expensive to spin up at scale.

The practical rule: use `async/await` for I/O-bound work (DB queries, HTTP calls, file reads). Offload CPU-bound tasks — image processing, crypto, ML inference — to a `worker_threads` pool. Libraries like `piscina` wrap this pattern cleanly.

Avoid `Promise.all` on CPU-heavy tasks thinking it parallelizes — it schedules microtasks, not threads.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Worker, isMainThread, parentPort, workerData } from 'worker_threads';

if (isMainThread) {
  const worker = new Worker(__filename, { workerData: { n: 42 } });
  worker.on('message', (result) => console.log('Fibonacci:', result));
} else {
  function fib(n: number): number {
    return n <= 1 ? n : fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);
  }
  parentPort?.postMessage(fib(workerData.n));
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
