INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e0c5882f-3152-4678-9b37-4858fae186cd',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Node.js Runtime — V8's JIT Pipeline and What It Means for Cold Starts$escape$,
  $escape$Node.js doesn't compile your JavaScript ahead of time — V8 interprets it first, then JIT-compiles hot paths. On startup, V8 parses and baseline-compiles your entire module graph before executing a single line. This is why large dependency trees murder cold start times in AWS Lambda and Azure Functions.

V8's pipeline: Ignition (bytecode interpreter) → Sparkplug (fast baseline JIT) → Maglev → TurboFan (optimizing JIT). Your `require()` chain at startup hits Ignition. Only after a function runs repeatedly does TurboFan kick in with type-specialized machine code.

Practical levers: Use `--max-old-space-size` to avoid GC pressure during warmup. Lazy-require heavy modules (`const heavy = () => require('heavy-lib')`) to defer parse cost. Node 18+ ships with V8 snapshot support — `--build-snapshot` lets you serialize the heap post-warmup and restore it on next boot, cutting cold starts by 40–60% in benchmarks. `vm.Script` with `cachedData` achieves similar gains for individual scripts by reusing bytecode across invocations.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Script } from 'vm';
import { readFileSync, writeFileSync, existsSync } from 'fs';

const src = readFileSync('./heavy-module.js', 'utf8');
const cacheFile = './heavy-module.cache';

let script: Script;
if (existsSync(cacheFile)) {
  const cachedData = readFileSync(cacheFile);
  script = new Script(src, { cachedData });
} else {
  script = new Script(src);
  writeFileSync(cacheFile, script.createCachedData());
}

script.runInThisContext();$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
